<h1 id="structure-and-operation-of-gates">Structure and operation of gates</h1><h2 id="voltage-regions">Voltage regions</h2><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="206"></p><p>We represent logical values with high and low voltages, and have an "undefined" / forbidden region in the middle which are invalid</p><p>In positive logic, high voltages correspond to <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> (normally used)</p><p>In negative logic, high voltages correspond to <span class="ql-formula" data-value="0">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> (weird)</p><p><br></p><h2 id="transistors">Transistors</h2><p>Logic circuits are built with transistors, which act like switches. Transistors have three terminals: <strong>Source</strong> ("input"), <strong>Gate</strong> (the source is compared to the gate) and <strong>Drain</strong> ("output"). </p><p><br></p><p>They conduct based on a voltage difference between the source and gate. If there's a big potential difference, they will conduct, for smaller differences they won't.</p><p><br></p><p>There are two types of transistors that we'll cover:</p><ul><li><strong>NMOS</strong>, <em>OFF</em> when a low voltage is applied to the gate (when the gate is <span class="ql-formula" data-value="0">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>), and <em>ON</em> when a high voltage is applied (when the gate is <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>). We connect the source to ground (<span class="ql-formula" data-value="0V">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span><span style="margin-right: 0.22222em;" class="mord mathdefault">V</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>)</li><li><strong>PMOS</strong>, <em>ON</em> when a low voltage is applied to the gate (when the gate is <span class="ql-formula" data-value="0">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>), and <em>OFF</em> when a high voltage is applied (when the gate is <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>). We connect the source to <span class="ql-formula" data-value="V_{DD}">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>D</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">V_{DD}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.83333em; vertical-align: -0.15em;"></span><span class="mord"><span style="margin-right: 0.22222em;" class="mord mathdefault">V</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.32833099999999993em;"><span class="" style="top: -2.5500000000000003em; margin-left: -0.22222em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span style="margin-right: 0.02778em;" class="mord mathdefault mtight">D</span><span style="margin-right: 0.02778em;" class="mord mathdefault mtight">D</span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.15em;"><span class=""></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span></li></ul><p><br></p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/iqMhsjB.png" width="609"></p><p><br></p><h2 id="gates-using-transistors">Gates using transistors</h2><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/PQOUC1R.png" width="286"></p><p>This is how all gates should look like:</p><ul><li>The PUN connects to high and should allow current to pass when the output should be high.</li><li>The PDN connects to ground and should allow current to pass when the output should be low.</li></ul><p><br></p><p>Note that the PUN and PDN should be inverses:</p><ul><li>PUN consists of PMOS transistors, since they are good at passing <span class="ql-formula" data-value="1">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; The<strong> fan-out</strong> is the amount of gates that are driven by a gate. The <strong>fan-in </strong>is the number of inputs of the gate.</p><p><br></p><p>As you can see, the rise and fall times depend on the fan-out:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/PG5Ru2Z.png" width="397"></p><p><br></p><p>When several inputs are connected to an output, the total load on that output is obtained by combining the loads of each input. In CMOS technology, it is generally assumed that the maximum load an output can</p><p>drive is about 12 – to maintain reasonable propagation times.</p><p><br></p><p>However just counting the amount of gates is not accurate enough, we have to count the amount of connected transistors:</p><ul><li><strong>Load factor:</strong> the amount of transistors that are driven by a certain input</li><li><strong>Total load:</strong> sum of all load factors</li></ul><p><br></p><h2 id="voltage-variations-and-noise-margins">Voltage variations and noise margins</h2><p>In real circuits, the wiring (or other external factors) can introduce noise. As you can see in the following image, we start off with two well-defined regions for high and low voltage. However, the noise can make these regions come closer together, this is called <strong>noise margin</strong>.</p><p><br></p><p>In order to make sure we can always differentiate between the two, we use a <strong>forbidden region</strong>, which should never be used as a aalue.</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Vdr4leY.png" width="483"></p><h1 id="bus">Bus</h1><p>We may want to connect different modules to a bus, but if one module outputs 0 and another outputs 1, we create a short-circuit:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/trBGTbE.png" width="149"></p><p><br></p><p>To tackle this, we use a tri-state buffer, in which at a given time, the output of only one module is selected for transmission:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/fXtpWro.png" width="269"></p><p>If input <span class="ql-formula" data-value="e">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">e</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.43056em;
